{
  "_metadata": {
    "model": "claude-fable-5",
    "cost_usd": 0.28683425,
    "duration_s": 58.238
  },
  "tool_calls": [
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "stm32 debug read-peripheral GPIOA",
        "description": "Read GPIOA registers via SVD-decoded debug attach"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "stm32 prog list-probes",
        "description": "List attached ST-LINK probes"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "cat stm32-project.jsonc 2>/dev/null || find .. -maxdepth 2 -name stm32-project.jsonc 2>/dev/null",
        "description": "Locate and show project descriptor"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "STM32_PROGRAMMER_DEFAULT_SN=066DFF485754727567021514 stm32 debug read-peripheral GPIOA",
        "description": "Read live GPIOA state on the L476RG (attach, no reset)"
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "I'll attach without reset and read GPIOA's live state \u2014 if main() hijacked PA13/PA14, their MODER fields will show plain input/output instead of the reset-default alternate-function mode.\nMultiple probes are attached \u2014 I need to pin one by serial.\nTwo boards on the bench (NUCLEO-L476RG and STM32N6570-DK). Let me check which one the current project descriptor targets.\nNo \u2014 the SWD pins are intact. I attached to the running target without reset (so this is the live, post-`main()` state) and read GPIOA via the SVD-decoded recipe:\n\n**PA13 (SWDIO):**\n- `MODER13 = 0b10` \u2014 alternate function (not GPIO input/output/analog)\n- `AFRH13 = 0` \u2014 AF0 = SWDIO\n- `PUPDR13 = 0b01` (pull-up), `OSPEEDR13 = 0b11` (very-high speed) \u2014 both the reset defaults for SWDIO\n\n**PA14 (SWCLK):**\n- `MODER14 = 0b10` \u2014 alternate function\n- `AFRH14 = 0` \u2014 AF0 = SWCLK\n- `PUPDR14 = 0b10` (pull-down) \u2014 reset default for SWCLK\n\nAlso `LCKR = 0` (no pin-config lock), so nothing froze a bad config either. The strongest corroborating evidence: the no-reset attach itself succeeded \u2014 if `main()` had stolen PA13/PA14, a live SWD halt-in-place would have failed (you'd have needed connect-under-reset).\n\nWhat the firmware *did* touch on port A: PA2/PA3 \u2192 AF7 (USART2, the ST-LINK VCP), and PA5 is in analog mode (`MODER5 = 0b11`) \u2014 note that's the LD2 LED pin on the L476RG, so if you expected the LED to be driven as an output right now, that's the anomaly worth looking at, not the SWD pins.\n\n(One bench note: both the L476RG and the N6570-DK are attached, so I pinned the probe with `STM32_PROGRAMMER_DEFAULT_SN=066DFF48...` \u2014 the bare one-shot failed with \"Multiple debuggers detected.\")"
}